        <body>       
                
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                April 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1887<lb/></p>
            <p>Reverend and Dear Sir&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have the<lb/> honor to submit my second monthly<lb/> report of the standing of the prepar&#45;<lb/>&#45;atory class of the Jewish Theological<lb/> Seminary.  During the month of<lb/> March the class has read Penta&#45;<lb/>teuch &#91;Hebrew&#93; the first chapter with &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> and grammatical explanations &#38; eight<lb/> Psalms with verbal commentary and<lb/> grammatical explanations&#44; in grammar<lb/> it has taken the segholate nouns&#44; and<lb/> in Biblical history has reviewed from<lb/> Exodus to Judges.  In Talmud it<lb/> has read the entire fifth and the<lb/> greater part of the sixth chapter of<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; with &#91;Hebrew&#93; and the most ess&#45;<lb/>ential &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; a part of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>of R. Samuel Hannagid and has<lb/> begun the Gemara of &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/>  According to the plan the class should<lb/> have begun with the Gemara of Be&#45;<lb/>rachoth but it was found necessary<lb/> to deviate in this particular as a suf&#45;<lb/>ficient number of copies of Berachoth<lb/> could not be obtained.  If deemed necessary<lb/> however&#44; this arrangement can be changed<lb/> as soon as sufficient copies of Berachoth<lb/> can be procured.  The pupils are without<lb/> exception progressing satisfactorily&#44; Kurz<lb/> and Simson are rapidly acquiring<lb/> English and will soon be fully up to<lb/> the standard of the class.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have the honor to remain&#44; Reverend Sir<lb/> very truly yours<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/> Preceptor<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
